<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet xml:id="sec-7-1">
        <title><m>\S 7.1</m>: Introduction to Limits</title>


                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Definition</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f: A \to \mathbb{R}</m>. The <term>limit</term> of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches
                            <m>a</m> is <m>L</m> if 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

				<exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Why do we require <m>0 \lt |x-a|</m> in Definition 7.1?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Why do you think we require <m>a</m> to be an accumulation point of the domain of <m>f</m>? What happens if <m>a \in \text{Dom}(f)</m> but <m>a</m> is not an accumulation point of <m>\text{Dom}(f)</m>? Such points are called <alert>isolated points</alert> of the domain of <m>f</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="8in">
                    <title>Example: Limits By Definition</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Prove <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 3}x^2 = 9</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Prove that <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1}(17x-42)=-25</m> using Definition 7.1.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                               Prove that <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2}x^{3}=8</m> using Definition 7.1.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Define <m>f:\mathbb{R}\to \mathbb{R}</m> via
<me>
  f(x) = \begin{cases}x,&#x26;\text{if }x \neq 0 \\ 17,&#x26;\text{if }x =0.\end{cases}
</me>
Prove that <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0}f(x)=0</m> using Definition 7.1.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Define <m>f:\mathbb{R}\to \mathbb{R}</m> via
<me>
  f(x) = \begin{cases}1,&#x26;\text{if }x \leq 0 \\ -1,&#x26;\text{if }x \gt 0.\end{cases}
</me>
Using Definition 7.1, prove that <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0}f(x)</m> does not exist.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Define <m>f:\mathbb{R}\to \mathbb{R}</m> via
<me>
  f(x) = \begin{cases}1, &#x26; \text{if } x \in \mathbb{Q} \\ 0, &#x26; \text{otherwise.
  }\end{cases}
</me>
Using Definition 7.1, prove that <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m> does not exist for all <m>a \in \mathbb{R}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Let <m>f</m> be a real function.
Prove that if <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m> exists, then the limit is unique.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>

                
                
                

        </worksheet>
    </article>
</pretext>